-A ran 70% of the 16h shift"}),seeAlso:["makespan"]},mps:{term:"MPS",aliases:["master production schedule"],short:"Master Production Schedule — the committed plan of what will actually be produced.",long:"Only MPS jobs count as allocated against raw material and capacity. Pending jobs must pass RM + Capacity checks before they can become MPS.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. 8 of your 12 pending API batches are approved to MPS",packaging:"e.g. the 50k Nestlé lids order is MPS; the rest are still pending"}),seeAlso:["rm-check","capacity-check","rush-order"]},"rm-check":{term:"RM check",aliases:["raw material check","material check"],short:"Verifies there is enough raw material stock to make this job.",long:"A job cannot become MPS until it passes this. Considers current stock minus what is already allocated to other MPS jobs.",examples:vs({pharma:'e.g. "Need 340kg of Solvent-X but only 200kg available"',packaging:'e.g. "Need 500 reels of BOPP film; 320 available, next PO lands Tue"'}),seeAlso:["mps","capacity-check"]},"capacity-check":{term:"Capacity check",aliases:["cap check"],short:"Verifies there is enough machine capacity to finish this job by its due date.",long:"Looks at the required routing, existing MPS load, shift calendar, and transit/changeover times. Fails if there is no feasible window.",examples:vs({pharma:'e.g. "Granulator-1 is booked solid for the next 6 days"',dairy:'e.g. "Filler-B cannot finish 10k bottles before Friday"'}),seeAlso:["mps","rm-check"]},changeover:{term:"Changeover",aliases:["setup","changeovers"],short:"The time it takes to switch a machine from making one product to another.",long:"Driven by rules (source SKU → target SKU). Without changeover rules the scheduler assumes zero-cost transitions, which is almost never realistic.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. 4h to switch Line-3 from Paracetamol API to Metformin API",packaging:"e.g. 45 min to change Flexo-A from black to cyan ink + clean plates",dairy:"e.g. 90 min CIP between Mango and Strawberry milkshake",inks:"e.g. 30 min wash between cyan and magenta offset ink"}),seeAlso:["setup-time","transit-rule","min-changeover"]},"setup-time":{term:"Setup time",short:"Non-productive time at the start of a task (including changeover).",long:"Stored per scheduled task as setup_time_minutes. The sum across a schedule is a good proxy for total changeover cost.",seeAlso:["changeover"]},"transit-rule":{term:"Transit rule",aliases:["machine transit","transit"],short:"Time required to move work-in-progress between two machines or sections.",long:"Used when a SKU routes through multiple steps on different machines. The scheduler inserts this delay between the predecessor finishing and the successor starting.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. 2h cooling delay between Granulation and Compression",packaging:"e.g. 30 min conveyor shift from Printing to Coating"}),seeAlso:["changeover","routing"]},routing:{term:"Routing",short:"The ordered sequence of steps (machines or lines) a SKU must pass through.",long:"Defined as REQUIRES_STEP edges on the SKU node. Each step has a minutes-per-unit rate. Can be section-based (discrete categories) or line-based (continuous lines).",seeAlso:["line-vs-section","transit-rule"]},"line-vs-section":{term:"Line vs. Section",short:"A Line is a continuous production flow; a Section is a discrete machine category.",long:'Line routing assigns a whole job to a named line (e.g. Line-3). Section routing picks any machine from a category (e.g. "any Granulator"). Tenants use one, the other, or both.',examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. Vasudha uses 8 named lines for APIs",packaging:"e.g. AnsaPack uses categories: Printing A, Printing B, Coating, Punching"}),seeAlso:["routing"]},ripple:{term:"Ripple",aliases:["ripple effect"],short:"The cascade of downstream changes caused by moving one task.",long:"When you push a job earlier (rush) or later (drag), tasks that shared a machine or followed in the routing must shift too. The scheduler flags ripple_overlap and ripple_routing changes.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. advancing Job-42 delays three other API batches by 6h each",packaging:"e.g. rushing the Nestlé order displaces two Amul runs to next shift"}),seeAlso:["rush-order"]},"rush-order":{term:"Rush order",aliases:["rush"],short:"Force a job to MPS even if it displaces others, with ripple impact shown upfront.",long:"Rush analysis estimates how many already-MPS jobs will be pushed late, and by how much, before you commit.",seeAlso:["ripple","mps"]},infeasibility:{term:"Infeasible",aliases:["infeasible"],short:"No valid schedule exists for this job under current constraints.",long:"Causes include: no machine can meet the routing, material is short, due date is impossible, or capacity is saturated. Each infeasible job carries a reason and (often) a bottleneck category.",seeAlso:["rm-check","capacity-check"]},edd:{term:"EDD (Earliest Due Date)",aliases:["earliest due date"],short:"Sort jobs by due date ascending. Oldest deadlines go first.",long:"Simple, interpretable, and good when due-date discipline matters more than throughput. Ignores job size and priority.",seeAlso:["priority","critical-ratio"]},priority:{term:"Priority",short:"Sort jobs by their manually-assigned priority number (lower = more urgent).",long:"Good when the business already has a clear ranking of customers or orders. Ties break on due date.",seeAlso:["edd"]},spt:{term:"SPT (Shortest Processing Time)",aliases:["shortest processing time"],short:"Run the quickest jobs first to maximise completions.",long:"Great for flushing small jobs and keeping WIP low, but long jobs can starve."},"critical-ratio":{term:"Critical Ratio",short:"(Time until due) ÷ (Time to complete). Lower ratio = more urgent.",long:"Balances due date and job size. A ratio below 1 means the job is already impossible on paper.",seeAlso:["edd"]},"max-utilization":{term:"Max Utilization",short:"Sort to keep the busiest machines fully loaded.",long:"Good for throughput; can worsen on-time performance if hot machines are given priority over due-date jobs.",seeAlso:["utilization"]},"min-changeover":{term:"Min Changeover",short:"Group similar jobs together to minimise switching time.",long:"Best when changeovers are expensive (pharma cleaning, ink wash-downs). Due dates can slip if not mixed with EDD.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. batch all Paracetamol SKUs before switching to Metformin",inks:"e.g. run all cyan orders before washing for magenta"}),seeAlso:["changeover"]},"on-time-percent":{term:"On-time %",aliases:["on-time","ontime"],short:"Percentage of jobs that finish on or before their due date.",long:"The single most important KPI for most planners. A schedule with great makespan and poor on-time is usually the wrong trade.",seeAlso:["makespan"]},"materials-first":{term:"Materials-first Planning",short:"Plan material availability first, then schedule production against it.",long:"For material-constrained shops (pharma APIs, specialty chemicals) where the real bottleneck is RM, not machines.",seeAlso:["rm-check"]},ksm:{term:"KSM",aliases:["key starting material"],short:"Key Starting Material — the critical raw material in pharma API manufacturing.",long:"Lead times are long (weeks to months), suppliers are few, and regulatory scrutiny is high. Usually the binding constraint on MPS.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. Atenolol KSM must be qualified by two suppliers before production"}),seeAlso:["rm-check"]},batch:{term:"Batch",short:"A single production run of a SKU with a fixed quantity.",long:"In materials-first mode a job may be split into multiple batches if a single batch exceeds machine capacity or material availability."},buffer:{term:"Buffer",short:"Spare capacity or time held back to absorb disruptions.",long:"Can be buffer inventory (safety stock), buffer time (slack in the schedule), or buffer capacity (unassigned machine hours)."},"reorder-point":{term:"Reorder point",short:"Stock level that triggers a new purchase order.",long:"Usually set as: (daily demand × lead time) + safety stock. Below this, you run out before replenishment arrives."},atp:{term:"ATP",aliases:["available-to-promise"],short:"Available-to-Promise — the quantity you can actually commit to a customer by a given date.",long:"Combines current stock, confirmed incoming POs, and production capacity, minus what is already allocated to other orders. An enquiry with positive ATP and an earliest-delivery ≤ due-date is safe to confirm.",examples:vs({pharma:"e.g. 4,000 vials ATP by April 20 — safe to quote a 3,500-vial order",packaging:"e.g. 0 ATP until May 2 because PET resin PO lands April 30"}),seeAlso:["reorder-point","mps"]}},rL=(()=>{var n;const t={};for(const s of Object.keys(ap)){t[s.toLowerCase()]=s;const a=ap[s];(n=a.aliases)==null||n.forEach(r=>{t[r.toLowerCase()]=s}),t[a.term.toLowerCase()]=s}return t})();function n1(t){const n=rL[t.toLowerCase().trim()];return n?ap[n]:void 0}function iL(t,n){if(!(!t.examples||t.examples.length===0))return t.examples.find(s=>s.industry===n)??t.examples.find(s=>s.industry==="generic")??t.examples[0]}const lL=[[/vasudha|pharma/i,"pharma"],[/convertpack|ansapack|packaging/i,"packaging"],[/godrej|jersey|dairy/i,"dairy"],[/organic\s+coatings|inks/i,"inks"],[/seatrace|avanti/i,"seafood"]];function oL(t){if(!t)return"generic";for(const[n,s]of lL)if(n.test(t))return s;return"generic"}function s1(){const{client:t}=fn();return u.useMemo(()=>oL(t==null?void 0:t.name),[t==null?void 0:t.client_id,t==null?void 0:t.name])}const dL=120;function Cn({term:t,children:n,inline:s=!0,underline:a="dotted"}){const r=n1(t);return r?e.jsx(cL,{entry:r,inline:s,underline:a,children:n}):(console.warn(`[GlossaryTerm] unknown term: "${t}"`),e.jsx(e.Fragment,{children:n??t}))}function cL({entry:t,inline:n,underline:s,children:a}){const r=s1(),[i,l]=u.useState(!1),[o,d]=u.useState(null),c=u.useRef(null),m=u.useRef(null),h=u.useRef(null),x=()=>{h.current!==null&&(window.clearTimeout(h.current),h.current=null),l(!0)},p=()=>{h.current!==null&&window.clearTimeo